msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "Basic Vehicle Requirements"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:76
msgid ""
"There are certain necessities for a truck that you need to have in place in "
"order for it to function within Rigs of Rods. Not including certain sections "
"can yield different results, from making the vehicle explode upon spawning, "
"to its nonappearance in the selection menu, to crashing the game outright. "
"Thus, it is important you get all the necessary sections in order before you "
"go about putting in the optional ones. Read through every section of this "
"because they're all necessary (except the cinecam and cameras sections when "
"dealing with loads/trailers)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "File Format"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:80
msgid ""
"Your vehicle should have a file format/suffix depending on its type. The "
"following table shows the types of vehicle and their formats."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block |
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:90
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| *Vehicle Type* | *File Format*\n"
"| Ground Vehicle | .truck\n"
"| Train | .train\n"
"| Air Vehicle | .airplane\n"
"| Sea Vehicle | .boat\n"
"| Trailer Load | .trailer\n"
"| Other Load | .load\n"
"| Machine/fixed object | .fixed\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:93
msgid ""
"For example, if I'm making a truck for Rigs of Rods, I might call it mytruck."
"truck, although obviously, what comes before the suffix is entirely up to "
"you."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "Directory"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:97
msgid "There are two different places to put your vehicle files."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:98
#, no-wrap
msgid "Vehicles Folder"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:101
msgid ""
"While editing your vehicle, it is best to put it in the \"vehicles\" folder "
"(`C:\\Documents and Settings\\Rigs of Rods\\vehicles` on Windows systems). "
"If, for example, one were creating `mytruck.truck`, then one would create a "
"folder within the `vehicles` folder called `mytruck`. Within this folder, "
"one would place \"mytruck.truck\" as well as all files associated with it. "
"(meshes, material files, etc.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:102
#, no-wrap
msgid "Zip Files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:105
msgid ""
"When one is preparing to release a vehicle, one ought to transfer it to a "
"zip file. This makes the file more portable and easier to release on the "
"Rigs of Rods Repository. To make a zip file for `mytruck.truck`, one would "
"take all the files contained within `mytruck` and place them in a zip "
"archive called `mytruck.zip`. This zip can then be moved to the `Packs` "
"folder (`C:\\Documents and Settings\\Rigs of Rods\\Packs` on Windows "
"systems)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:106
#, no-wrap
msgid "Title"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:109
msgid ""
"You should name your vehicle before you go about doing anything else. The "
"title must go on the very first line of the file. For example, if I want my "
"vehicle to be called `My Truck`, on Line 1 of my vehicle's file I put `My "
"Truck`. Type it in as you want it to appear on the menu - there is no "
"special syntax to worry about."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:110
#, no-wrap
msgid "Globals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:113
msgid ""
"Here, we set our vehicle's mass, the mass of the load nodes and the material "
"to be used on your vehicle. If you're planning on using a mesh, then you can "
"just use `tracks/semi` for the material, but if you're going to use a "
"<<{baseurl}/truck-description-file/index.adoc#submesh,Submesh>> to give your "
"vehicle its appearance, it's a requirement."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:119
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"globals\n"
";dry mass, cargo mass, material\n"
" 10000.0,  1000.0,     tracks/semi\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:122
msgid ""
"The globals section comes before the nodes and beams. The first number, *dry "
"mass*, defines the mass, in kilograms, our vehicle will attempt to be. (each "
"node has a minimum mass of 50kg.) The second number, called the \"cargo mass"
"\", defines the mass of the nodes whose flag (see <<First Beams and Nodes>>) "
"is `l`. These nodes are also known as the load nodes. The material, as "
"stated above, defines the material and texture that is to be used on the "
"submesh sections of your truck. This part of the globals is not important if "
"you are going to make it fully out of a mesh (or multiple meshes), in which "
"case you may simply use the material `tracks/semi`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:123
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:376
#, no-wrap
msgid "Engine"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:126
msgid ""
"This section is not necessary for a trailer or other load (unless you want "
"to be able to get in your trailer or load [to activate custom flares on the "
"trailer, for example]). It is also not necessary in airplanes or boats. In "
"order to get into your vehicle, you will need an engine, so it's necessary "
"for all the other vehicle types. You can find out how to use the engine "
"section here: <<Engine>>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:127
#, no-wrap
msgid "Nodes & Beams"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:130
msgid ""
"You'll need nodes and beams - these are what make up any vehicle you see in-"
"game. See <<First Beams and Nodes>>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:131
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cameras & Cinecam"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:134
msgid ""
"These two sections are not at all needed if you're making a trailer or other "
"load, unless you need to be able to enter the trailer (for example, to "
"activate custom flares on it)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:136
msgid "However, all the other types of vehicle do need these sections."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cameras"
msgstr ""

#. type: Named 'title' AttributeList argument for macro 'image'
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:139
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cameras location"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:139
#, no-wrap
msgid "cameras.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:146
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"cameras\n"
";center, rear, left\n"
" 0,      1,    2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:149
msgid "'''"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:151
msgid ""
"The above guide image and example should prove quite helpful in creating "
"cameras. The cameras section has to come after the nodes and beam sections, "
"and it consists of 3 numbers. These 3 numbers are nodes that have been "
"defined in the nodes section, and are used to define the position of the "
"vehicle. The pitch and roll indicators (and the similar attitude indicators "
"in aircraft), for example, use these camera nodes to get the orientation of "
"the vehicle. It also, as the name suggests, orients the camera views."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:153
msgid ""
"The first node is the centre node, and it must be aligned with both the rear "
"and the left nodes, as is visible in the guide image. The rear node must be "
"behind the centre node, so that if you look at the vehicle from the front, "
"the rear node is hidden by the centre node. The left node should be to the "
"left of thecentre node, so that if you look at the vehicle from the right, "
"the left node is hidden by the centre node."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:154
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cinecam"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:161
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"cinecam\n"
";x,   y,   z,   8 bindings,              spring, damping\n"
"0.66, 2.0, 1.8, 75,76,77,78,73,74,53,54, 8000.0, 800.0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:164
msgid ""
"The cinecam node is a node suspended with 8 beams used to define the "
"position of the interior/first-person camera of your vehicle. Like the "
"cameras section it must come after the nodes & beam sections."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:166
msgid ""
"The first 3 values define the position of the cinecam node, and are fairly "
"self-explanatory. Like the nodes section, these values are in metres."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:168
msgid ""
"The next 8 values are nodes. Rigs of Rods will create beams from each of "
"these nodes to your cinecam, in order to hold it in place."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:170
msgid ""
"The final 2 values define the spring and the damping factors of the beams "
"that support your camera. The spring factor defines how stiff the beams are "
"- the higher this number, the more stiff your camera is in terms of its "
"position. The damping factor defines the beams' resistance to motion."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:172
msgid ""
"Those 2 values are *optional*, and if you don't include them the values will "
"default to a spring rate of 8000.00 and a damping factor of 800.00."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:173
#, no-wrap
msgid "The End"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:176
msgid ""
"The final requirement for the file is a simple three-letter word, \"end\". "
"This is the very last line of your file and simply closes your vehicle file. "
"If you don't have this, Rigs of Rods may crash or have other issues (for "
"example, sometimes the lack of the \"end\" means that physics will never be "
"calculated upon the vehicle)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:177
#, no-wrap
msgid "First beams and nodes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:182
msgid ""
"Nodes and beams are the building blocks of vehicles and loads in Rigs of "
"Rods. Anything can be simulated with nodes and beams if the right settings "
"are put in. Nodes and beams are what you will be using to create your "
"vehicles."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:186
msgid ""
"Think back to geometry class. Remember points? Nodes are essentially points. "
"All beams are simply defined as a link between two nodes. A node is defined "
"by the following code:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:192
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
";number,    x,    y,    z, options\n"
"      0, 0.00, 0.75, 0.66,       n\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:195
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Number*: Each node has a number, starting from zero.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:196
#, no-wrap
msgid "*X*: The x-position of the node on a Cartesian coordinate system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:197
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Y*: The y-position of the node on a Cartesian coordinate system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:198
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Z*: The z-position of the node on a Cartesian coordinate system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:200
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Options*: Options can change the way nodes behave. Valid options are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:211
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"** `f`: Nodes with this option will not produce sparks when contacting hard surfaces.\n"
"** `x`: Nodes with this option will emit smoke.\n"
"** `y`: This is the exhaust reference point- the direction that smoke is emitted is opposite the direction of this node relative to the exhaust point.\n"
"** `c`: Nodes with this option will not contact the ground or collision meshes.\n"
"** `h`: A node with this option will lock onto another node when the \"L\" key is pressed ingame.\n"
"** `e`: A node with this option will become a point by which objects can be added to the terrain. (try out the terrain editor truck for an example of how this works.)\n"
"** `b`: Nodes with this option will have extra buoyancy.\n"
"** `p`: Nodes with this option will not emit particles of any kind.\n"
"** `L`: Nodes with this option will have information about them recorded to the RoR.log file.\n"
"You can have multiple options on a node. See <<{baseurl}/truck-description-file/index.adoc#nodes,Nodes>> for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:212
#, no-wrap
msgid "set_node_defaults"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:215
msgid ""
"set_node_defaults is a command which can be inserted anywhere within the "
"nodes section to change the way nodes following the command behave. For "
"syntax, see <<{baseurl}/truck-description-file/index.adoc#set_node_defaults,"
"TDF documentation>>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:219
msgid ""
"Beams are the structural components of your truck/airplane/boat/hovering "
"death machine. These are like those line segments you learned about in "
"geometry class. (aren't you glad that you paid attention?). See <<{baseurl}/"
"truck-description-file/index.adoc#beams,TDF documentation>> for more "
"information."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:220
#, no-wrap
msgid "set_beam_defaults"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:223
msgid ""
"set_beam_defaults is a command which can be inserted anywhere within the "
"beams section to change the way beams following the command behave. The "
"settings are shown in their default state below. To return a setting to its "
"default state, one can simply put \"-1\" as the setting."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:228
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"                 ;springiness, damping, deformation threshold constant, breaking threshold constant, beam diameter, beam material, plastic deformation coefficient\n"
"set_beam_defaults     9000000,   12000,                         400000,                     1000000,          0.05,   tracks/beam,                             0.0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:230
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Springiness*: Defines the stiffness of the beam. Higher values make the beam stiffer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:232
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Damping*: Defines the beam's resistance to motion. Higher values make the beam less likely to deform.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:234
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Deformation Threshold Constant*: The amount of force which must be applied to a beam before it does not return to its original length. The lower the value, the easier it is to deform.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:236
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Breaking Threshold Constant*: The amount of force which must be applied to a beam for it to break. The lower the value, the easier it is to break.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:238
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Beam Diameter*: The size of the beam, visually speaking. Measured in meters. *Beam Material*: The material used to color the beam. It must be defined in a separate material file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:240
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Plastic Deformation Coefficient*: The amount of force (a factor) to deform a geometrical shape (i.e. a vehicle made of nodes and beams). For example, if a cube made of nodes and beams is crashed to a wall, then the placement of the nodes are displaced, altering the original shape to an irregular one. This also affects the length of beams, if nodes are displaced, the beams may conform to a new shorter or longer length, and staying that way until another outside force is applied.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:242
msgid ""
"For more information, see <<{baseurl}/truck-description-file/index."
"adoc#set_beam_defaults,set_beam_defaults>>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:243
#, no-wrap
msgid "Rigidity"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:248
msgid ""
"Welcome to the guide to Rigidity in Rigs of Rods, This guide is to making a "
"sturdy vehicle for Rigs of Rods, by interconnecting the nodes in a \"X\" to "
"create a strong chassis."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:250
msgid ""
"If you do not have a \"X\" shape interconnecting your beams, your chassis "
"will be very Flimsy, Which in turn is bad, right?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:251
#, no-wrap
msgid "Preparing your chassis"
msgstr ""

