#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:353
msgid ""
"All wheels are able to do skid steering. See the <<braked_steering,"
"steering>> chapter."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:354
msgid "It is considered good form to keep your rays between 10 and 20."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:355
#, no-wrap
msgid "Axles"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:358
msgid ""
"This section defines axles on a vehicle, allowing more accurate distribution "
"of torque among the wheels."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:360
msgid "Sample axle section"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:366
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"axles\n"
"w1(1 2), w2(3 4), d(ol) ; axle 1\n"
"w1(5 6), w2(7 8), d(l) ; axle 2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:369
msgid ""
"The axle section introduces open differentials, and Spooled (aka locked) "
"differentials. By adding axles to your vehicle file you override the "
"propulsed property for the tires. Only wheels connected to an axle are "
"powered, if multiple axles are defined the axles are interconnected in a "
"locked manner. If no axle section is defined the old model of equal power "
"distribution is used. Because the axle sections looks up already defined "
"wheels, it must be defined **AFTER** the wheels have been defined."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:370
#, no-wrap
msgid "Problems?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:373
msgid ""
"Wheel weight has a big effect on top speed since heavy wheels have lots of "
"rolling resistance in RoR. Try to make the wheels as light as possible. If "
"the wheels explode, they probably have too high damping for the weight. If "
"the wheels and rpm needle start shaking, set lower clutch torque in the "
"engoption section. This can take some tweaking, but it's worth it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:375
msgid ""
"Used together with fusedrag and realistic truck weight, real torque is often "
"enough so there's no need to have several thousand hp engines. That makes "
"the trucks easier to drive and better handling."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:379
msgid ""
"The engine sections are used for vehicles which are driven through their "
"wheels (trucks). Together, they specify the type of engine being used (truck "
"or car), the power of that engine and the gear ratios for the truck."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:380
#, no-wrap
msgid "engine"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:383
msgid ""
"This section specifies torque, gearing and RPM ranges of the engine being "
"used."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:384
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:429
#, no-wrap
msgid "Syntax"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:391
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"engine\n"
";min rpm, max rpm, torque, differential, reverse, neutral, 1st,   2nd,  3rd,  4th,  5th,  6th...                  Terminator\n"
" 1000.0,  1500.0,  8000.0, 2.00,         10.85,   10.00,   13.86, 9.52, 6.56, 5.48, 4.58, 3.83, 3.02, 2.53, 2.08, -1.0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:394
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Minimum RPM* - The engine speed in which the automatic transmission downshifts and the clutch engages.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:395
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Maximum RPM* - The engine speed in which the automatic transmission upshifts. Actual redline is 120% of this speed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:396
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Torque* - A number representing the 'torque' of the engine. The higher the value, the faster a truck will accelerate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:397
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Differential ratio* - A global gear conversion ratio. (Final gear reduction ratio)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:398
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Rear gear ratio* - Gear ratio of reverse. For every turn of the wheel the engine will have to turn this many times (not counting the differential ratio).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:399
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Neutral gear ratio* - Gear ratio of neutral gear. 1.0 is a good one as it helps to distinguish between reverse and forward gears\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:400
#, no-wrap
msgid "*First gear ratio* - Gear ratio of 1st gear\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:402
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Second/etc gear ratio* - Gear ratio of second/etc gears.\n"
"There must be between 3 and 15 forward gears. The last gear *must be followed by a -1 value*.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:404
msgid "====== Detailed Syntax"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:406
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Torque*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:408
msgid ""
"RoR uses a Flat torque model, usually correct for large intercooled turbo "
"diesels. The unit is unknown: Neither N.m nor ft.lbf Tuning torque in RoR is "
"a tricky topic, since the current air resistance simulation is overstrong. "
"Setting torque to provide realistic acceleration at low speeds results in "
"severely stunted top speeds. Setting it to provide higher top speeds results "
"in very strong acceleration."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:410
msgid ""
"Engine Inertia also has a *VERY* important role in engine behavior since "
"this value also determines how fast a vehicle can accelerate."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:412
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Differential ratio*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:414
msgid ""
"Differential ratio represents gear reduction ratio between input pinion gear "
"and the ring gear of the differential. This parameter acts as global gear "
"conversion ratio. It means that if, let's say first gear has ratio 13.86 and "
"differential ratio is 2.0, actual first gear reduction is 27.72 (2.0 * "
"13.86). If you are using real gearbox parameters, bear this in mind and look "
"for real differential ratios too."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:416
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Gear ratios*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:418
msgid ""
"Gear ratios of forward gears. For every turn of the wheel must engine turn "
"this many times (not counting the differential ratio). When setting various "
"gear ratios, try to make smaller difference between higher gears. Pleas note "
"that in sample gear setting the difference (ratio) between first and second "
"gear is approx. 45 %, but difference between the fifth and sixth gear is "
"about 19 %. This allows smoother gearbox performance. There must be between "
"3 and 15 forward gears. *The last gear must be followed by a -1 value.*"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:419
#, no-wrap
msgid "More information"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:422
msgid ""
"A great source of practical gear ratios is from link:http://roadranger.com/"
"Roadranger/productssolutions/transmissions/index.htm[Eaton Fuller]. To see "
"the ratios, click the name of the transmission and find *Product "
"Specifications Guide*. If your vehicle decelerates in a gear you may not "
"have enough power, or too high a gear. NOTE: the value of this site is "
"unknown. RoR's poor air resistance simulation probably invalidates the use "
"of any real life gear ratios: It's always best to make sure a truck can "
"sensibly use all the gears it has."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:424
msgid ""
"If you know a little about vehicles there is a link:http://grimmjeeper.com/"
"gears.html[Gear Ratio Guide], but a decent knowledge of transmissions, "
"transfer cases, underdrives and correct rear end gears is highly recommended."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:425
#, no-wrap
msgid "engoption"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:428
msgid ""
"This optional section allows the user to specify whether the engine is for a "
"car or heavy truck and the engine inertia of the vehicle."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:435
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"engoption\n"
"0.5, c\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:438
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Engine inertia*: the engines resistance to change in RPM.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:439
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Engine type*: the type of engine inside the vehicle. Use (c) for car engines and (t) for truck engines.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:441
msgid "====== Detailed syntax"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:443
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Engine inertia*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Named 'title' AttributeList argument for macro 'image'
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:444
#, no-wrap
msgid "Different inertia models."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:444
#, no-wrap
msgid "engine-inertia-models.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:447
msgid ""
"The default game value is 10.0, which is correct for a large diesel engine, "
"Use higher values to make engines accelerate more slowly and stall more "
"difficultly, which may be useful for vehicles towing large masses. This "
"value should be lowered for smaller, light engines (Is the multiplier "
"different for car and truck engines?)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:449
msgid ""
"With a high value of inertia the engines RPM is not likely to change when "
"resistance is met. As an example, when changing gears a high inertia will "
"cause the wheels to slip, while a lower value will cause the engine RPM to "
"change and prevent the wheels from slipping. However, with a low inertia and "
"a high brake value, the engine will stall more easily since the brakes can "
"change the RPMs more easily."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:451
msgid ""
"If your engine doesn't change its RPM's during gear change, your engine "
"inertia is too high"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:453
msgid ""
"If a vehicle is feeling sluggish, and hard to brake, it is better to "
"decrease the inertia than increase the brake force, and torque."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:455
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Engine type*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:457
msgid ""
"Using `c` for cars or `t` for trucks specifies characteristics of the "
"engines. Car engines use a different sound to truck engines and have no "
"turbocharger. They also have less inertia by default. `t` is the default."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:458
#, no-wrap
msgid "Torque curve"
msgstr ""

#. type: Named 'title' AttributeList argument for macro 'image'
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:460
#, no-wrap
msgid "Torque curve for a small diesel engine."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:460
