#. type: Title =====
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:535
#, no-wrap
msgid "Dependent suspension"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:538
msgid ""
"The wheels of each axle are securely connected to each other using non "
"independent suspension systems. The force from every bump that a wheel on "
"one side goes over is transmitted into the other wheel too. These systems do "
"not tend produce very good handling, and therefore are not often used on "
"sports cars. Non independent suspension is much more commonly found on heavy "
"duty vehicles, where the link between the wheels makes axles much stronger."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:540
msgid "====== Beam axle"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:542
msgid ""
"Beam axles are an extremely simple form of suspension, almost always seen on "
"the back axles of vans and semi trailers. The wheels are directly attached "
"to the axles, and cannot change their angle to it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:544
msgid ""
"The easiest way to create a beam axle is to use <<axle-rigidity/index.adoc#,"
"Axle Rigidity>> nodes."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/source/docs/rorbook/index.adoc:546
msgid ""
"The lateral location of a beam axle can be controlled in a number of ways; "
"the easiest way in RoR simply to weakly truss the two arms that hold the "
"axle, but this is generally not possible in real life and limits how much "
"the axle can roll."
